# migrated from tests/cases/calibrate.chat (hermetic + isolated, perf-held)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test calibrate]
!timeout 0
# gen142 (E8): metacognitive calibration. The agent reports HOW it knows the last
# conclusion, with confidence language COMPUTED from the real proof state, and
# answers "why do you think that?" / "what would make you change your mind?" from
# that state. Five epistemic states, each with DIFFERENT grounded language.
# Held-out names (rex/zara/socrates/alice) and predicates.

# INFERRED — derived through a rule. Confidence cites the proof chain; the lever
# is the load-bearing premise found by ablation.
> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates).
> every man is a mortal
< Learned rule: mortal(X) :- man(X).
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< I'm confident but it's derived, not given: mortal(socrates) because man(socrates). I concluded it by applying a rule, so it's only as sound as those premises.
> what would make you change your mind?
< It hangs on one premise: if I learned that socrates is a man were false, I'd stop concluding socrates is a mortal.

# KNOWN — a direct stored fact. Certain; the lever is contradicting the fact.
> rex is a dog
< Learned: dog(rex).
> is rex a dog?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< I'm certain: rex is a dog is a fact you stated directly, so I hold it as known, not inferred.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Learning that rex is NOT a dog — that's the single fact it rests on, so contradicting it would overturn my belief.

# UNKNOWN — known predicate, unknown entity. Honest absence of support.
> is zara a dog?
< No.
> why do you think that?
< I don't actually think that — I have no support for zara being a dog, so I can't claim it either way.

# CONFLICTED — both polarities stated. Genuinely unsure; both claims named.
> alice is a person
< Learned: person(alice).
> alice is not a person
< Learned: not person(alice).
> is alice a person?
< No.
> why do you think that?
< I'm genuinely unsure — I hold conflicting claims about alice: you told me it is a person and also that it is not. Until that's resolved I can't commit either way.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Telling me which to trust — you've claimed both that alice is a person and that it is not. Retract one and I'd settle on the other.

# HYPOTHETICAL — a standing supposition. Conditional; the lever is dropping it.
> suppose tweety is a bird
< All right — assuming tweety is a bird. Anything I conclude from it will be conditional on that.
> is tweety a bird?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< Only conditionally: tweety is a bird holds because I'm ASSUMING tweety is a bird. Drop that assumption and I'd have no ground for it.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Dropping the assumption — I only conclude tweety is a bird because I'm supposing tweety is a bird. Withdraw that and the conclusion goes with it.

